04578nam a22005655i 9780774854092DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20071984xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748540927 a10.59962/97807748540922doi  a(DE-B1597)662055  a(OCoLC)748214591  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1089.W55.P46 1984eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a94200aLetters from Windermere, 1912-1914 /ced. by Elizabeth Phillips, R. Cole Harris. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©1984  a1 online resource (277 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Pioneers of British Columbia00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction -- tLetters from Windermere -- tIndex -- tThe Pioneers of British Columbia0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWritten primarily by Daisy Phillips, with a few by her husband Jack, to her family in England, these letters describe the creation of a shortlived English home in the Windermere Valley of southwestern British Columbia. Not given to introspection, Daisy registers her immediate and frank reactions to her new environment and startling new way of life. From her letters we learn of the experiences of the Phillips and their neighbours in settling the newly opened land and of their attempts to grow fruit in an area with limited agricultural potential. The contrast between middle-class British mores and those of Canadian pioneer society -- largely classless and multi-ethnic in character -- was to Daisy a challenge to be overcome. Requests to England brought in return a flood of British consumer goods which helped her to duplicate in her dress and household furnishings the more cultivated surroundings and manners of home. While such affectations seemed incongruous in a frontier setting, Daisy learned to work to maintain them and mastered tasks unknown in England to one of her station. Between her first request for a pamphlet on laundering handkerchiefs and her departure less than three years later, she learned to cook on a wood stove, sew, clean house, and wash clothes without running water or servants. There is also evidence that prior to their abrupt return to England at the outbreak of war, the cultural barriers were breaking down as the Phillips became more involved in sharing the experience of being pioneer Canadians. Jack's early death on the battlefield gives Daisy's letters an added poignancy. Not only do they constitute a valuable historical document but they also convey with simple directness the story of a happy marriage, of the intersection of an English dream with the Windermere Valley, and something of the story of all immigrants to any new settlement in Western Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFrontier and pioneer lifezBritish ColumbiazWindermere Lake Region. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aHarris, R. Cole, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPhillips, Elizabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311141940440uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485409240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774854092423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774854092/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141940-4  University of British Columbia eBook-Package Pre-20